---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import { slate } from '../../data/slate.js';

// Case number, prev/next, and counts derive from slate order — see src/data/slate.js.
const idx = slate.findIndex((c) => c.slug === 'porte');
const self = slate[idx];
const num = String(idx + 1).padStart(2, '0');
const prev = slate[(idx + slate.length - 1) % slate.length];
const next = slate[(idx + 1) % slate.length];
---
<!--
  ============================================================================
  Remaining (deferred): 3 image frames.
  Resolved: Client = Porte (Populous, named once, neutrally — no ACE reference) ·
            Role = Director of UX · 2019 · Capacity = lead of 3-person UX team ·
            reflection x3 + feature set + cupcake principle from your notes ·
            no support-call number, so outcomes lead with ratings + SUS.
  ============================================================================
-->
<Base title="Porte — research-first mobile banking · uxward" bodyClass="case">

  <div class="container breadcrumb">
    <div class="grid">
      <div class="marker">§ ↩</div>
      <div><a href="/work">— Back to all work</a></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="container title-block">
    <div class="grid">
      <div class="marker">§ 00</div>
      <div>
        <span class="case-num">{num}</span>
        <h1 class="case-title" set:html={self.title} />
        <p class="case-deck">
          Populous's first mobile-only bank had to stand out in a saturated market, for a generation
          it had never designed for. We researched and tested every layer — app, card, mailer, brand —
          before a line of code was written, and shipped a 1.0 that earned 4.8 stars.
        </p>
        <div class="artifact hero-preview">
          <div class="frame">
            <span class="placeholder-label">Hero preview</span>
            <span class="placeholder-detail">
              The case's signature screen — the strongest visual, shown up front.
            </span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="container">
    <div class="meta-strip">
      <div class="grid">
        <div class="marker">§ ✻</div>
        <div class="meta-row">
          <div class="cell">
            <div class="label">Client</div>
            <div class="value">Porte (Populous)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="cell">
            <div class="label">Role</div>
            <div class="value">Director of UX</div>
          </div>
          <div class="cell">
            <div class="label">Timeframe</div>
            <div class="value">2019</div>
          </div>
          <div class="cell">
            <div class="label">Capacity</div>
            <div class="value">Lead of a 3-person UX team</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="cs">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="grid">
        <div class="marker">§ 01</div>
        <div>
          <div class="cs-eyebrow"><span class="num">01</span>— Context —</div>
          <h2 class="cs-head">A fifty-year-old bank, designed for <em>nobody under forty.</em></h2>
          <div class="cs-prose">
            <p>
              Porte's parent, Populous, had been in financial services for more than fifty years. In
              all that time it had never built anything for the way younger people actually bank —
              mobile-first, on their own terms.
            </p>
            <p>
              Porte was the answer: a mobile-only bank built for the underbanked and aimed squarely at
              college students. The ambition wasn't a digital copy of the old bank — it was the account
              those students wished existed, one that helped them understand and grow their money
              instead of just storing it.
            </p>
            <p>
              The brief was a hard one. Launch a brand-new mobile bank into a market already full of
              polished apps, and give a generation that had never been Populous's customer a reason to
              choose it.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="cs">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="grid">
        <div class="marker">§ 02</div>
        <div>
          <div class="cs-eyebrow"><span class="num">02</span>— The problem, named clearly —</div>
          <h2 class="cs-head">In a saturated market, "another banking app" is <em>dead on arrival.</em></h2>
          <div class="cs-prose">
            <p>
              Every neobank and legacy player already had a mobile app, most of them competent. A
              merely-adequate Porte would be invisible — it had to be a reason to switch, not a box
              ticked.
            </p>
            <p>
              And it was being built by a company with deep banking experience but no track record
              designing for this customer. The pull to ship a thin first version and iterate later was
              strong — and, in a crowded market, fatal.
            </p>
            <blockquote class="cs-pullquote">
              We didn't need another banking app — we needed the bank we all wished we'd had.
            </blockquote>
            <p>
              <strong>The problem: launch a fifty-year-old institution's first mobile-only bank into a
              saturated market — and give a generation it had never served a reason to choose it over
              the apps they already trusted.</strong>
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="cs">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="grid">
        <div class="marker">§ 03</div>
        <div>
          <div class="cs-eyebrow"><span class="num">03</span>— The approach —</div>
          <h2 class="cs-head">Know the customer cold before you build <em>anything.</em></h2>
          <div class="cs-prose">
            <p>
              The obvious path was to design from the team's instincts and benchmark against the
              category leaders. We did the opposite. Before committing to a direction, we went to the
              customer — on-premise intercept interviews about how they bank, what they value, and what
              they want from their money.
            </p>
            <p>
              Then we tested relentlessly, at every layer. We signed up for every major mobile bank and
              ran real banking tasks through each to find where they shined and where they failed. We
              ran information-architecture studies to shape the flows, usability rounds on low-fidelity
              prototypes, and — before a single line of code — repeated studies against the
              high-fidelity prototype with real customers, on-site and remote, to settle IA, UX, UI,
              accessibility, and usability up front.
            </p>
            <p>
              The research worked so well the engagement grew: we went on to design and test the card
              itself, the mailer and unboxing, the brand, the teaser films, the marketing site, and the
              copy. By the end, every member of the team — designer, PM, developer — felt they knew the
              customer personally.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="choices">
            <div class="choice-row">
              <div class="key">— Chose to —</div>
              <div class="val"><strong>Test every layer before writing code.</strong> The high-fidelity prototype had to pass real-customer studies before a line was built.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="choice-row">
              <div class="key">— Chose to —</div>
              <div class="val"><strong>Design the whole experience, not just the app.</strong> Card materials, the mailer unboxing, the brand, the teaser films, the copy — all researched and tested.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="choice-row">
              <div class="key">— Chose to —</div>
              <div class="val"><strong>Train my two designers as researchers</strong> while we ran the studies — so the people designing Porte understood its users firsthand, not from a report.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="choice-row">
              <div class="key">— Chose <strong>not</strong> to —</div>
              <div class="val">Ship code before the experience was validated. Buildout started only after the prototype tested clean.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="choice-row">
              <div class="key">— Chose <strong>not</strong> to —</div>
              <div class="val">Let the team's taste decide. When we argued over colors, fonts, or features, the user's needs settled it — not egos.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="choice-row">
              <div class="key">— Chose <strong>not</strong> to —</div>
              <div class="val">Imitate the category leaders. The competitive teardown was to learn where they'd gone wrong, not what to copy.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="cs">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="grid">
        <div class="marker">§ 04</div>
        <div>
          <div class="cs-eyebrow"><span class="num">04</span>— The work itself —</div>
          <h2 class="cs-head">A whole experience, not a <em>single screen.</em></h2>
          <div class="cs-prose" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-9);">
            <p>
              The work was the entire Porte experience, researched and designed end to end. Three pieces
              of it stand in for the rest.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="artifacts">
            <div class="artifact">
              <div class="frame">
                <span class="placeholder-label">Artifact 01 / 03</span>
                <span class="placeholder-detail">
                  The high-fidelity Porte app — home dashboard showing round-up savings, budgeting, and
                  color-coded spending, on a phone.
                </span>
              </div>
              <div class="caption-grid">
                <span class="num">01</span>
                <div class="body">
                  <h4>The bank, designed before it was built</h4>
                  <p class="cap">
                    The product real customers tested before any code: round-ups into a high-yield
                    savings account, every-purchase donations to a charity of your choice, virtual and
                    youth cards, and budgeting that helped users understand and improve how they spend.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="artifact">
              <div class="frame">
                <span class="placeholder-label">Artifact 02 / 03</span>
                <span class="placeholder-detail">
                  The Porte card and its mailer — card materials, packaging, and the welcome layout,
                  shot flat-lay.
                </span>
              </div>
              <div class="caption-grid">
                <span class="num">02</span>
                <div class="body">
                  <h4>The card and the unboxing</h4>
                  <p class="cap">
                    We designed and tested the physical product too — card materials, the mailer, the
                    layout, the first-touch experience — because a mobile bank's first impression often
                    arrives in the mail.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="artifact">
              <div class="frame">
                <span class="placeholder-label">Artifact 03 / 03</span>
                <span class="placeholder-detail">
                  The launch kit — teaser-video stills, social posts, and marketing-site screens in the
                  Porte identity.
                </span>
              </div>
              <div class="caption-grid">
                <span class="num">03</span>
                <div class="body">
                  <h4>The brand and the launch</h4>
                  <p class="cap">
                    Teaser films, social concepts, the marketing site, and the copy — each researched
                    and tested for imagery, tone, and message before launch, so the whole funnel spoke
                    with one voice.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="cs-prose" style="margin-top: var(--space-9);">
            <p>
              We designed more than a first release could carry. Several of the most ambitious features
              were genuinely hard to build and didn't make 1.0 — many still sit in the backlog years
              later. But they were researched and designed, so the roadmap was drawn long before the
              engineering caught up.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="cs outcomes-bleed">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="grid">
        <div class="marker" style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.78);">§ 05</div>
        <div>
          <div class="cs-eyebrow"><span class="num">05</span>— Outcomes —</div>
          <h2 class="cs-head">
            A fifty-year-old bank's first mobile app shipped to 4.8 stars — and a lighter support load than its older siblings.
          </h2>
          <div class="outcomes-stats">
            <div class="stat">
              <div class="label">— App Store rating —</div>
              <div class="figure">4.8 ★</div>
              <div class="desc">iOS, across 3,400+ reviews — 4.7★ on Android.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="stat">
              <div class="label">— Usability —</div>
              <div class="figure">85%+</div>
              <div class="desc">SUS scores in testing; 4.5/5 on aesthetics.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="stat">
              <div class="label">— Reviews —</div>
              <div class="figure">12,000+</div>
              <div class="desc">Combined across iOS and Android since launch.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="cs">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="grid">
        <div class="marker">§ 06</div>
        <div>
          <div class="cs-eyebrow"><span class="num">06</span>— Reflection —</div>
          <h2 class="cs-head">What I'd reverse. What I <em>carried forward.</em></h2>
          <div class="cs-prose">
            <p>
              <strong>The decision I'd reverse:</strong> we trusted third-party vendors who swore their
              micro-apps and APIs would be ready by ship date. They weren't. When the devs went to build
              what we'd designed, the tools couldn't support it and offered no APIs to hook into — so 1.0
              shipped with their clunky embedded micro-apps bolted in, unstyleable, unable to match
              Porte's look. The result was a Frankensteined first version that compromised the very UX
              and UI we'd tested so hard to get right. The vendors fixed it eventually, and Porte looks
              great today — but I'd never again design against a capability a vendor only promises to
              have later.
            </p>
            <p>
              <strong>The surprise:</strong> how low the bar actually is. It is not hard to build a
              banking app that looks and feels the way people want — and yet so many feel two decades
              old. The reason, I learned, is rarely the design team; it's the archaic internal systems
              and third-party micro-apps banks are forced to build on. Even in 2019, making something
              modern out of that legacy plumbing was like pulling teeth. The constraint was never the
              design — it was the foundation.
            </p>
            <p>
              <strong>What I carried forward:</strong> this was the project where we stopped saying
              "MVP." Minimum viability doesn't make a good product. We shipped a <em>minimum lovable
              product</em> instead — a "cupcake": small in scope but complete across every layer, with
              enough great UX, reliability, and polish to be genuinely loved at 1.0. We've run on the
              cupcake, birthday-cake, wedding-cake model ever since. Ship something whole and lovable,
              never something barely viable.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="container">
    <div class="prevnext">
      <div class="pn-cell prev">
        <div class="label">— Previous case —</div>
        <a href={`/work/${prev.slug}`} set:html={`— ${prev.title}`} />
      </div>
      <div class="pn-cell next">
        <div class="label">— Next case —</div>
        <a href={`/work/${next.slug}`} set:html={`${next.title} —`} />
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="back-all">
      <a href="/work">— Back to all {slate.length} selected pieces →</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</Base>
